tags: indexFlame
Game Loop
The game loop is the heart of the app, is where things get live. In na nutshell, is a infinite loop which continuously runs through simple steps, update the game state and create more game states, to flame engine, you run 30 to 60 fps

Game Instantiation
That is the path to run your code:

Game Lifecycle
The game Loop will re-render every ùö´t, so if you have a ùö´t = 6, the game will re-render every 6s with a precisely of microseconds.

When we override some functions that are essencial to run the app, exemple:
import &#039;package:flutter/material.dart&#039;;

class someClass extends FlameGame{
	@override
	Future&lt;void&gt;? onLoad(){
		print(&quot;&lt;gameLoop&gt; onLoad() called&quot;);
		return super.onLoad();
	}

	@override
	void update(double dt){
		super.update(dt);
		print(&#039;&lt;gameLoop&gt; update method called&#039;);
	}

	void render(Canvas canvas){
		super.render(canvas);

		print(&#039;&lt;gameLoop&gt; render method called&#039;);
	}

}
This will call those prints ever those methods are called. When we have such a thing, we can see this game-process in action ‚Üí onLoad() is called just one time, updade() is called every dt seconds and the render only after the update

